Scenario: The adoption walkthrough is structured so a coding agent handed the documentation can execute the bootstrap without inferring intent
  Given the shopsystem-docs repository contains an adoption walkthrough (one or more linked markdown files)
  When the walkthrough's markdown is parsed for structural elements
  Then every step the adopter must execute is presented as a fenced code block whose language tag identifies the command surface (e.g., bash, sh, shell) or as an explicit named instruction inside a numbered list
  And every command block contains a single concrete invocation with literal arguments (no placeholders left to the reader's judgement; any value the adopter must substitute is named in a preceding sentence with the exact replacement token)
  And every step that produces an observable side effect (a created repo, a running container, a registered BC) is followed by a verification step (a command to run, an output to check, or a URL to load) whose expected result is stated explicitly
  And the walkthrough does not contain forks of the form "if you are a human do X, if you are an agent do Y" — the same instructions serve both audiences
